{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = |birth_date = {{Birth year|1922}} |birth_place = [[Baranovichi]], [[Poland]] |Year of Aliyah = 1936 |death_date = {{nowrap|{{Death date and age|1986|09|04|1922|||df=yes}}}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1969|7]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1973|8]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|10]] |party1 = [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]] |partyyears1 = 1969–1977 |party2 = [[Mapam]] |partyyears2 = 1977 |party3 = [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]] |partyyears3 = 1981–1984 }}
'''Dov Zakin''' ({{lang-he|דב זכין}}, 1922 &ndash; 4 September 1986) was an [[Israel]]i politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for the [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]] and [[Mapam]] between 1969 and 1977 and again from 1981 until 1984.
==Biography== Born in [[Baranovichi]] in [[Poland]] in 1922, Zakin made [[aliyah]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1936. He was educated at the [[Ben Shemen Youth Village]], before studying political Science and economics at [[Tel Aviv University]].
In 1945 he was amongst the founders of kibbutz [[Lehavot HaBashan]]. The following year he helped found the [[Wadi Ara]] branch of the Eretz Yisrael Workers Union. In 1950, 1952 and 1963 he travelled to the [[United States]] as an emissary for [[Hashomer Hatzair]], and between 1959 and 1961 served as secretary of the Peace Movement.
A member of the Mapam secretariat, he was elected to the Knesset on the Alignment list (an alliance of Mapam and the [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]]) in [[Israeli legislative election, 1969|1969]]. He was re-elected in [[Israeli legislative election, 1973|1973]], and in 1977 was part of the Mapam faction that briefly broke away from the Alignment.<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/faction/eng/FactionHistoryAll_eng.asp Mergers and Splits Among Parliamentary Groups] Knesset website</ref> He lost his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|1977 elections]], but returned to the Knesset after the [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|1981 elections]]. He lost his seat for a final time in [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|1984]]. In 1986 he became a member of the board of directors of the [[World Zionist Organization]].
He died in 1986.
