{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|Брускина, Мария Борисовна|date=November 2014}} {{refimprove|date=February 2013}} [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1972-026-43, Minsk, Widerstandskämpfer vor Hinrichtung.jpg|thumb|300px|Masha Bruskina with fellow resistance members before hanging. The placard reads "We are the partisans who shot German troops", [[Minsk]], October 26, 1941]] <!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image: Masha bruskina.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Execution of Masha Bruskina. The plate reads "We are the partisans who shot German troops"]] --> '''Maria "Masha" Bruskina''' ({{lang-be|Марыя Барысаўна Брускіна}} ''Marïya Barïsawna Bruskina''; {{lang-ru|Мария Борисовна Брускина}} ''Mariya Borisovna Bruskina''; 1924 &ndash; 26 October 1941 in [[Minsk]]<ref>http://spartacus-educational.com/2WWbruskina.htm</ref>) was a [[History of the Jews in Belarus|Belarusian Jewish]] member of the [[Minsk]] [[Belarusian resistance during World War II|Resistance]] during [[World War II]].<ref>http://www.auschwitz.dk/masha.htm</ref> She volunteered as a nurse at the hospital in the Minsk Polytechnic Institute, which had been set up to care for wounded members of the [[Red Army]]. In addition to caring for the soldiers, she helped them escape by smuggling civilian clothing and false identity papers into the hospital. A patient told the Germans what Bruskina was doing, and she was arrested on October 14, 1941, by members of the [[Wehrmacht]]'s [[707th Security Division (Wehrmacht)|707th Infantry Division]] and the 2nd Schutzmannschaft Battalion,<ref>[http://laws.lp.findlaw.com/getcase/7th/case/973067.html USA v KAZYS CIURINSKAS]</ref> [[Lithuanian Auxiliary Police Battalions|Lithuanian auxiliary troops]] under the command of Major [[Antanas Impulevičius]]. After being arrested, Bruskina wrote a letter to her mother on October 20, 1941:
{{quotation|I am tormented by the thought that I have caused you great worry. Don't worry. Nothing bad has happened to me. I swear to you that you will have no further unpleasantness because of me. If you can, please send me my dress, my green blouse, and white socks. I want to be dressed decently when I leave here.}}
==Biography== Masha Bruskin lived in Minsk with her mother, senior goods manager of the Book Trade Office of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|BSSR]] State Publishing House. She studied well and read a lot. She was also a [[Vladimir Lenin All-Union Pioneer Organization|pioneer leader]] and a member of the school committee of [[Komsomol]]. in December 1938, the newspaper ''Pioneer of Belarus'' published a photograph of Masha with the caption: "Masha Bruskina - the schoolgirl of 8th grade in school № 28, Minsk. She has only good and excellent marks in all subjects". In June 1941, Maria Bruskina graduated from Minsk secondary school № 28.
==The execution== Local German authorities decided on a public hanging to make an example of Bruskina, along with two other members of the resistance, 16-year-old Volodia Shcherbatsevich and [[World War I]] veteran Kiril Trus. Before being hanged, she was paraded through the streets with a placard around her neck which read, in both [[German language|German]] and [[Russian language|Russian]]: "We are [[Soviet partisans|partisans]] and have shot at German troops". Members of the resistance were made to wear similar signs whether or not they had actually shot at German troops. She and her two comrades were hanged in public on Sunday, October 26, 1941, in front of Minsk Kristall, a yeast brewery and distillery plant on Nizhne-Lyahovskaya Street (15 Oktyabrskaya Street today). The Germans let the bodies hang for three days before allowing them to be cut down and buried.<ref>http://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa12790</ref>
Pyotr Pavlovich Borisenko witnessed the execution:
{{quotation|When they put her on the stool, the girl turned her face toward the fence. The executioners wanted her to stand with her face to the crowd, but she turned away and that was that. No matter how much they pushed her and tried to turn her, she remained standing with her back to the crowd. Only then did they kick away the stool from under her.}}
Olga Shcherbatsevich, the mother of Volodia Shcherbatsevich, was hanged the same day as her son with two other members of the resistance in front of the [[National Academy of Sciences of Belarus]].<ref>''A Historical Injustice: the case of Masha Bruskina''; by Nechama Tec and Daniel Weiss, University of Connecticut in Stamford, ''Johns Hopkins University Holocaust and Genocide Studies''; 1997 11(3):366-377; {{doi|10.1093/hgs/11.3.366}}</ref>
==Identification and remembrance== For decades after the war, Bruskina was officially referred to only as "the unknown girl", allegedly due to [[antisemitism]] from Soviet authorities.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=D0ojAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zM4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1880%2C348797 | title=Did Soviets hide identity of executed teen in 1941? | work=The Palm Beach Post | date=Sep 16, 1987 | accessdate=30 May 2015 | author=Keller, Bill | pages=D1}}</ref> Up to 2009, Bruskina's name was not acknowledged on the memorial plaque at the execution place. However, since 2009, a new memorial plaque at the execution place has been placed. The Russian inscription now reads "Here on October 26, 1941 the Fascists executed the Soviet patriots K. I. Truss, V. I. Sherbateyvich and M. B. Bruskina". Bruskina was first recognized in the 1960s, as most of her family and friends had been killed in the [[Minsk Ghetto]].<ref>http://spartacus-educational.com/2WWbruskina.htm</ref> A monument for Bruskina was erected in [[HaKfar HaYarok]] in [[Israel]], and a street was named after her in [[Jerusalem]].
<center> <gallery perrow="3" widths="250" heights="200"> file:Oktyabrskaya street Minsk 7b.jpg|Commemorative at the entrance of Minsk yeast plant, at the place of execution K.I. Trus, V. I. Scherbachevich and M. B. Bruskina. file:Oktyabrskaya street Minsk 7d.jpg|Memorial plaque with the name of M. Bruskina (from August 2008). file:Memorial to Jewish Women Fighters, Israel.jpg|Monument in memory of M. Bruskina and other Jewish women, who fought against the Nazis. Kfar Ha-Yarok, Israel. </gallery> </center>
