{{use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox person |name = Mohamed Yousri Salama |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{birth date|1974|10|01|df=yes}} |birth_place = Alexandria, Egypt |death_date = {{death date and age|2013|03|24|1974|10|01|df=yes}} |death_place = Alexandria, Egypt |residence = |nationality = [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] |alma_mater = |occupation = Dentist, writer |years_active = |net_worth = |boards = |religion = |spouse = |children = |parents = |signature = |website = }}
'''Mohamed Yousri Salama''' ({{lang-ar|محمد يسري سلامة}}, 1 October 1974 &ndash; 24 March 2013) was an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] politician, writer and activist.
==Early life and education== Salama was born in [[Alexandria]] on 1 October 1974.<ref name=ahr24mar/> He was the son of a professor of literature at [[Alexandria University]] and his mother was a poet.<ref name=kor1apr>{{cite news|last=Kortam|first=Hend|title=Profile: On the life and death of Mohamed Yousry Salama|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/03/27/profile-on-the-life-and-death-of-mohamed-yousry-salama/|accessdate=1 April 2013|newspaper=Daily News Egypt|date=27 March 2013}}</ref> He studied dentistry.<ref name=ene24mar/> He also studied theology in Alexandria.<ref name=eind24mar/> His teachers were Salafi preachers, including Mohamed Ismail Al Moqadem, who has a tolerant approach.<ref name=eind24mar/>
==Career== Salama began to work as a dentist in his own clinic.<ref name=kor1apr/> However, he left the job and worked as a researcher and translator at the Bibliotheca Alexandrina Manuscript Centre.<ref name=ahr24mar>{{cite news|title=Egypt mourns Mohamed Yousri Salama|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/67611/Egypt/Politics-/Egypt-mourns-Mohamed-Yousri-Salama.aspx|accessdate=25 March 2013|newspaper=Ahram Online|date=24 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=eind31mar>{{cite news|title=Late activist's wife discusses fellow Salafis' criticism of her husband|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/late-activist-s-wife-discusses-fellow-salafis-criticism-her-husband|accessdate=1 April 2013|newspaper=Egypt Independent|date=31 March 2013}}</ref> He joined politics during [[Egyptian Revolution of 2011|the Egyptian revolution]] in 2011.<ref name=lina27mar/> After the revolution, he became a member and spokesperson of the [[Salafist]] [[Nour Party]].<ref name=msn24mar>{{cite news|title=Egypt mourns Mohamed Yousri Salama|url=http://arabia.msn.com/news/middle-east/1748032/egypt-mourns-mohamed-yousri-salama/|accessdate=25 March 2013|newspaper=MSN|date=24 March 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328080359/http://arabia.msn.com/news/middle-east/1748032/egypt-mourns-mohamed-yousri-salama/|archivedate=28 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He left the party due to disagreements in August 2011.<ref name=ene24mar/> Then he joined the liberal [[Constitution Party (Egypt)|Constitution Party]] led by [[Mohamed ElBaradei]] and became one of its founding members.<ref name=how1oct>{{cite news|last=Howeidy|first=Amira|title=Egypt's political coalitions and new parties: A guide|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/54309/Egypt/Politics-/Egypts-political-coalitions-and-new-parties-A-guid.aspx|accessdate=25 March 2013|newspaper=Ahram Online|date=1 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=cendowment>{{cite journal|title=Al Dostour (Constitution Party)|journal=Carnegie Endowment|url=http://egyptelections.carnegieendowment.org/2012/10/31/al-dostour-constitution-party-2|accessdate=19 April 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607055418/http://egyptelections.carnegieendowment.org/2012/10/31/al-dostour-constitution-party-2|archivedate=7 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ami1116>{{cite journal|last=Howeidy|first=Amira|title=What's in a name?|journal=Al Ahram Weekly|date=27 September – 3 October 2012|volume=1116|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2012/1116/eg3.htm|accessdate=22 April 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105045835/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2012/1116/eg3.htm|archivedate=5 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, Salama was one of the senior figures of the party and a member of its supreme body.<ref name=eind24mar>{{cite news|title=Dostour member Mohamed Yousry Salama dies at 39|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/dostour-member-mohamed-yousry-salama-dies-39|accessdate=25 March 2013|newspaper=Egypt Independent|date=24 March 2013}}</ref>
===Works=== Salama published several books. He also wrote for several Egyptian newspapers, including ''[[Al Shorouk]]'', ''[[Al Masry Al Youm]]'' and ''[[Al-Dostour (Egypt)|Al Dostour]]''.<ref name=ahr24mar/> In addition, his articles were published as book chapters. One of his articles published in August 2012 deals with the relationships between Copts and Salafists in the Egyptian context.<ref name=alm>{{cite web|title=Copts after 25th of January|url=http://www.almesbar.net/eng/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=136:68_copts-after-25th-of-january&Itemid=62|publisher=Al Mesbar Studies and Research Center|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>
==Death and funeral== Salama died of stomach disease at the age of 38 on 24 March 2013 in Alexandria.<ref name=ene24mar>{{cite news|last=Enein|first=Ahmad Aboul|title=Mohamed Yousry Salama passes away|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/03/24/mohamed-yousry-salama-passes-away/|accessdate=25 March 2013|newspaper=Daily News|date=24 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=lina27mar>{{cite news|last=Attalah|first=Lina|title=Obituary: Mohamed Yousry Salama|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/obituary-mohamed-yousry-salama|accessdate=1 April 2013|newspaper=Egypt Independent|date=27 March 2013}}</ref> His funeral was held in Alexandria on 25 March 2013.<ref name=kor1apr/>
